          "type": "heading",
          "settings": {
            "heading": "How to C<em>hoose</em> the Right Parrot Toys?",
            "heading_size": "large",
            "heading_style": "default",
            "heading_tag": "h2",
            "highlight_option": "underline-hand",
            "word_animation_color": "#fe0126"
          }
        },
        "text_wgxWBi": {
          "type": "text",
          "settings": {
            "text": "<p>The best toy is the one your bird will actually use. Aim for a mix and rotate often.<br/><br/><strong>1) Match the toy to your bird’s “vibe”</strong><br/>\t•\tChewers: tougher wood, thick paper, palm, and durable components<br/>\t•\tShredders: paper, sola, vine balls, cardboard, soft shreddables<br/>\t•\tForagers / brainy birds: toys with hidden treats, cups, drawers, or crinkle paper<br/>\t•\tClimbers: rope, ladders, swings, and multi-point hang toys<br/><br/><strong>2) Choose the right toughness</strong><br/>\t•\tSmall birds usually prefer lighter materials they can destroy quickly.<br/>\t•\tBig birds often need heavier-duty toys so they don’t obliterate them in 30 seconds.<br/><br/><strong>3) Get the size right</strong><br/>A good rule: your bird should be able to grab, pull, and manipulate parts without getting overwhelmed by a massive toy.<br/><br/><strong>4) Always grab a “toy mix”</strong><br/>We recommend keeping 3 types in rotation:<br/>\t•\t1 shreddable<br/>\t•\t1 chew toy<br/>\t•\t1 foraging or interactive toy<br/><br/>Swap toys weekly to keep things exciting.<br/><br/><strong>5) Safety check</strong><br/>If it’s fraying, cracking, or has loose parts, it’s time to repair or replace.</p>"
          }
        }
